eches, pantaloons, hose’. In 1484 these were ‘chauces of yron or legge harneys’ (   OED  ). Middle English  <i>chauce</i> was a general term for anything worn on the feet: boots, shoes, hose, or leggings. As Baldwin le Chaucer (1307   London Letter Books   B) was of  <i>Cordwanerstrete</i>, the early  <i>chaucer</i> was probably a worker in leather, a maker of leather breeches, boots, etc."],"variants":[{"name":"London Letter Books","meanings":["1  English: nickname, variant of the Norman name   Petchey   (Old French  <i>peché</i>, Middle English  <i>peche</i> ‘sin’). Medieval spellings with final  <i>-e</i> can represent either  <i>peché</i> or  <i>peche</i>, so some of the earliest of the following bearers may belong with  <i>Petchey</i> rather than  <i>Petch</i>, but the two forms of the name were in any case interchangeable. Compare John Peche, tailor, 1320, identical with J. Pecchee, 1328 in   London Letter Books   E; John Peche, 1558, Moses Pechey, 1584 in   IGI   (West Hanningfield, Essex).","2  English: variant of   Spetch   with loss of initial  <i>S-</i> (unless  <i>Spetch</i> itself is a variant of  <i>Petch</i> with a prosthetic  <i>S-</i>). The two names were certainly interchangeable.   Redmonds, Dictionary of Yorks Surnames   notes Michael Petch or Spetch (1609–13) and Lancelot or Lance Petch or Spetch (1625–7) in the Leeds parish registers; and Benjamin Petch otherwise Spetch, 1764 in   WR Yorks Quarter Sessions   (Azerley, WR Yorks). Compare also Thome Peche, 1586, Margret Spetche, 1594 in   IGI   (Londonthorpe, Lincs); Thomas Spech, 1589, Richd. Petch, 1726 in   IGI   (Whitgift, WR Yorks)."]},{"name":"Causer","meanings":["English (West Midlands): probably a variant of <b>Chauser</b>, an occupational name for a maker of leggings or other apparel for the legs or feet, from an agent derivative probably of a northern variant of Old French <i>cauc(i)er</i>, <i>chaucier</i> ‘maker of hose, shoemaker’, although <i>Cauc(i)er</i>, the Norman and Picard form of the name, has not yet been noted in English medieval records. Alternatively, perhaps a variant of <b>Cosier</b>, an occupational name from Middle English <i>cosere</i> ‘horse dealer’."]},{"name":"OED","meanings":["Hebrew name, meaning ‘upholder, encourager’, borne in the Bible by a prophet who persuaded the Israelites to release the captives that they had taken from the kingdom of Judah (2 Chronicles 28:9–15). It is a popular modern Hebrew name."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705188,"age":7,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705189,"age":42,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705190,"age":73,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. Chaucer was born about 1217, in England. She had at least 1 son with Chaucer."},"et":{"about 1217–":"umbes 1217–Surnud","1213–Male":"1213–Surnud","1230–1280":"1230–1280","1217–Female":"1217–Surnud","1217":"1217","1259":"1259","about 1217":"umbes 1217","1224":"1224","1213":"1213","1230":"1230","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","Ipswich, Suffolk, England":"Ipswich, Suffolk, England","England":"England"},"fi":{"about 1217–":"noin 1217–Kuollut","1213–Male":"1213–Kuollut","1230–1280":"1230–1280","1217–Female":"1217–Kuollut","1217":"1217","1259":"1259","about 1217":"noin 1217","1224":"1224","1213":"1213","1230":"1230","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","Ipswich, Suffolk, England":"Ips